<DESCRIPT>  OAKLAND; BERKELEY; MOUNTAIN; FIRE; CHARITY; AID; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  (box) Finding people: For help in contacting family members, call the American
Red Cross at (510) 535-2840 or (510) 535- 2888. Relatives living outside the
Bay Area are asked to call their local Red Cross chapters.; (box) Homes: Those
evacuated may find out when they can return to their homes by calling two
special Oakland Fire Department lines: (510) 287-6021 and (510) 287-6000.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOW TO GET OR GIVE HELP  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Oakland Hills Fire; See also related stories on pages 1A and 14-18A of
this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  (box) Messages: Messages from friends and family members of fire victims can
be left at the kiosk at Chimes Market, College and Keith avenues near the BART
Rockridge station in Oakland.; (box) Hot lines: For general help, the Red
Cross can be reached at (510) 535-2883; University of California, Berkeley
students, families and employees can call (510) 642-4335; Kaiser Permanente
employees can call (510) 987-4672; Berkeley residents can call the city's
disaster information line, (510) 644-6993.; (box) Shelters: In Oakland, the
shelter is at Oakland Technical High School, 4351 Broadway; in Berkeley, the
shelter is at Haas Clubhouse at UC-Berkeley on Centennial Drive, behind
Memorial Stadium.; (box) Temporary housing: Eden I&amp;R Inc. of Hayward, a
non-profit corporation, will try to match fire victims with housing. Those who
need housing can call (510) 537-2552; those who can supply housing can call
(510) 537-2710. Collect calls will be accepted from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Cort
Furniture Rental Corp. also is helping people find temporary housing. Call
(415) 952-9791.; (box) Health: For 24-hour information on smoke inhalation and
other fire-related health problems, call Ask a Nurse, Alta Bates-Herrick
Hospital, (800) 322-1322.; (box) Mental health: For help with fire-related
anxiety or grief, call Alameda County's 24-hour crisis intervention line at
(510) 849-2212. A mental health line in Berkeley can be reached at (510)
644-8562.; (box) Schools: Seven Oakland public schools are open today: Arts,
Far West, Joaquin Miller, Montclair, Montera, Thornhill and Whittier.
Claremont and Oakland Tech are scheduled to reopen Thursday, provided they are
no longer needed by the city. Claremont is serving as a command center;
Oakland Tech as a shelter. Kaiser, Hillcrest and Chabot are tentatively
scheduled to reopen Monday, provided Pacific Gas &amp; Electric Co. can restore
power to them. All Berkeley public schools are open today. The California
College of Arts and Crafts reopens today.; (box) Transportation: A six-mile
stretch of Highway 13, connecting Highway 24 with Interstate 580 in Oakland,
was reopened Tuesday. All on-ramps to Highway 13 are open. Access to and from
Highway 13 from I-580 is unrestricted. Access to Highway 13 from Highway 24 is
allowed only from westbound Highway 24 to southbound Highway 13. There is no
access from Highway 24 to northbound Highway 13 because traffic is still
restricted in Berkeley. All off-ramps from Highway 13 are open except the
Moraga/Thornhill and Broadway Terrace exits. Tunnel Road between Hiller Drive
and Ashby Avenue will remain closed indefinitely.; (box) Insurance: Fire
victims wanting help with fire insurance claims may call the toll-free state
Department of Insurance hot line at (800) 927-HELP.; (box) Mail: Anyone who
wants to receive mail addressed to devastated areas can call (510) 874-8200.
Displaced people are asked to establish a permanent mailing address and file a
change-of-address form. For further information, call (510) 874-8200.; (box)
Phones: Pacific Bell is offering free services to evacuees. For voice-mail
service, call toll-free (800) 427-7715, ext. 345. For call-forwarding service,
call a Pacific Bell business office. Pacific Bell expects to have restored
service tonight to homes that survived in the fire area. Pacific Bell also is
providing telephones at emergency shelters so victims can make free calls
within the 510, 415, 408 and 707 area codes. Veterans with Cal-Vet homes may
call (800) 626-1613 toll-free. Transamerica Insurance Co. customers can call
(800) 628-3102.; (box) Pets: For emergency boarding for displaced or lost
pets, call the Marin Humane Society, (415) 883-4621, or the San Francisco
Department of Animal Care and Control at its 24-hour hot line, (415) 554-9400.
Volunteers at Pets Unlimited, at (415) 563-6700, also are available to help
find lost pets. The Oakland chapter of the Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals has established a fund to provide emergency services to
animals. Contributions can be made by check to the Oakland SPCA Fire Fund,
8323 Baldwin St., Oakland 94621. For information, call (510) 569-0702.; (box)
Donations: Clothing, bedding, non-perishable food and bottled drinks will be
accepted at all Salvation Army Thrift Stores. All Bay Area Safeway stores are
accepting non-perishable food, diapers, batteries and emergency supplies (no
clothing). Lucky stores are accepting non-perishable food, batteries, cups,
plates and utensils, flashlights, bottled water, etc., at their Alameda County
and Contra Costa County stores.; (box) Relief center: Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory has set up an emergency relief center that is receiving
donations of food, emergency supplies, disposable diapers and personal
products from 9 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. at the visitors' center, Those who have
temporary housing for fire victims can call the laboratory at (510) 422-9797.;
(box) Clothing drive: KSOL radio station in San Mateo will help gather
clothing donations from sites around the Bay Area and deliver it to relief
agencies. The station number is (415) 341-8777; fax number is (415) 574-9355.;
(box) South Bay: The Campbell Seventh-day Adventist Church is accepting
donations of supplies and food. The drop-off center will be open from 9 a.m.
to 6:30 p.m. at 600 W. Campbell Ave., Campbell.; (box) Contributions: The East
Bay Community Foundation is reactivating its Disaster Relief Fund and is
taking contributions to be given to non-profit groups offering resettlement,
counseling and other support services. Send contributions to the East Bay
Community Foundation, 6230 Claremont Ave., Fourth Floor, Oakland 94618, or
call (510) 658-5441.; Donations also may be made to East Bay Emergency Fire
Fund, United Way at 410 Bush St., San Francisco 94108, or 1970 Broadway, No.
340, Oakland 94612. For more information, call (415) 772-HELP, (800) 273-6222,
or TTY 554, 2445 for the hearing-impaired.; Contributions can also be sent to
the American Red Cross at 2111 E. 14th St., Oakland 94606, or 1550 Sutter St.,
San Francisco 94109; or the Salvation Army at P.O. Box 2D, San Jose 95109. The
American Red Cross is accepting credit card donations at (510) 535-2812 or
-2818. All Northern California Lucky and Safeway stores also are accepting
donations.  </TEXT>
